erser</i>, <i>marser</i> ‘textile merchant’, in which final <i>-er</i> has been weakened to <i>-ey</i>.","(of Norman origin): habitational name from Marcy in France (Manche)."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret de Mascy was born in 1253, in Cheadle, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with Geoffrey de Cheadle Dutton III. She died in 1293, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1253–1293":"1253–1293","1230–1294":"1230–1294","1272–Male":"1272–Surnud","1280–1326":"1280–1326","about 1272":"umbes 1272","1326":"1326","1253":"1253","1230":"1230","1272":"1272","1294":"1294","1293":"1293","1280":"1280","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, England","Nether Tabley, Cheshire, England":"Nether Tabley, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1253–1293":"1253–1293","1230–1294":"1230–1294","1272–Male":"1272–Kuollut","1280–1326":"1280–1326","about 1272":"noin 1272","1326":"1326","1253":"1253","1230":"1230","1272":"1272","1294":"1294","1293":"1293","1280":"1280","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, England","Nether Tabley, Cheshire, England":"Nether Tabley, Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"1253–1293":"1253–1293","1230–1294":"1230–1294","1272–Male":"1272–Décédé","1280–1326":"1280–1326","about 1272":"environ 1272","1326":"1326","1253":"1253","1230":"1230","1272":"1272","1294":"1294","1293":"1293","1280":"1280","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, Angleterre","Nether Tabley, Cheshire, England":"Nether Tabley, Cheshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Margaret de Mascy est née en 1253, à Cheadle, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 2 fils avec Geoffrey de Cheadle Dutton III. Elle est décédée en 1293, à l’âge de 40 ans."},"de":{"1253–1293":"125